Azure Auto Scaling Overview

In Azure, Virtual Machine Scale Sets (VMSS) provide auto-scaling for VMs.
______________________
VMSS defines a set of identical VMs.

Integrates with Load Balancer to distribute traffic.

Can scale out/in based on:

CPU / Memory usage

Number of requests (via LB metrics)

Custom metrics
_______________________________
1️⃣ VM Scale Set
resource "azurerm_linux_virtual_machine_scale_set" "vmss" {
  name                = "demo-vmss"
  resource_group_name = azurerm_resource_group.rg.name
  location            = azurerm_resource_group.rg.location
  sku                 = "Standard_B2s"
  instances           = 2   # initial count
  admin_username      = "azureuser"

  source_image_reference {
    publisher = "Canonical"
    offer     = "0001-com-ubuntu-server-jammy"
    sku       = "22_04-lts"
    version   = "latest"
  }

  os_disk {
    caching              = "ReadWrite"
    storage_account_type = "Standard_LRS"
  }

  network_interface {
    name                                   = "vmss-nic"
    primary                                = true
    ip_configuration {
      name                                   = "ipconfig"
      subnet_id                              = azurerm_subnet.private.id
      primary                                = true
      load_balancer_backend_address_pool_ids = [azurerm_lb_backend_address_pool.lb_backend.id]
    }
  }

  admin_ssh_key {
    username   = "azureuser"
    public_key = file("~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub")
  }

  health_probe_id = azurerm_lb_probe.http_probe.id

  upgrade_mode = "Manual"
}
____________________________________________
2️⃣ Autoscale Settings
resource "azurerm_monitor_autoscale_setting" "autoscale" {
  name                = "vmss-autoscale"
  resource_group_name = azurerm_resource_group.rg.name
  target_resource_id  = azurerm_linux_virtual_machine_scale_set.vmss.id
  location            = azurerm_resource_group.rg.location

  profile {
    name = "autoscale-cpu"
    capacity {
      default = 2
      minimum = 1
      maximum = 5
    }

    rule {
      metric_trigger {
        metric_name        = "Percentage CPU"
        metric_resource_id = azurerm_linux_virtual_machine_scale_set.vmss.id
        time_grain         = "PT1M"
        statistic          = "Average"
        time_window        = "PT5M"
        time_aggregation   = "Average"
        operator           = "GreaterThan"
        threshold          = 70
      }

      scale_action {
        direction = "Increase"
        type      = "ChangeCount"
        value     = 1
        cooldown  = "PT5M"
      }
    }

    rule {
      metric_trigger {
        metric_name        = "Percentage CPU"
        metric_resource_id = azurerm_linux_virtual_machine_scale_set.vmss.id
        time_grain         = "PT1M"
        statistic          = "Average"
        time_window        = "PT5M"
        time_aggregation   = "Average"
        operator           = "LessThan"
        threshold          = 30
      }

      scale_action {
        direction = "Decrease"
        type      = "ChangeCount"
        value     = 1
        cooldown  = "PT5M"
      }
    }
  }
}
___________________________
Explanation (Interview-ready)

VMSS: A group of identical VMs that automatically integrates with LB backend pool.

Health Probe: Ensures traffic only goes to healthy VMs.

Autoscale Setting:

Default = 2 VMs

Min = 1, Max = 5

Scale out if CPU > 70%

Scale in if CPU < 30%

Benefits:

Horizontal scaling (adds/removes VMs)

Seamless integration with Load Balancer

Pay-as-you-use, cost optimized
_________________________
Internet → LB Public IP → LB Rule → VMSS Backend Pool → VMs
                                     ↑
                            Autoscale monitors CPU
                            and adjusts VM count
